    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-09-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-09-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="107"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d107">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.659/3</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Child</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-09-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 10, 1923</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to the Department’s circular telegram
                    dated June 12, 1923, 3 P.M., forwarded from the American Embassy at Paris, and
                    to subsequent communications concerning the proposal for a treaty to be
                    concluded between the United States and Italy with respect to the enforcement of
                    prohibition on Italian vessels within <pb facs="0301" n="185" xml:id="pg_185"/>
                    American territorial waters and measures for stopping liquor smuggling, the
                    Department encloses for your information a copy of an instruction, dated August
                    25, 1923, addressed to the American Embassy at London dealing with the
                        matter.<note n="40" xml:id="d107fn40">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_172">p. 172</ref>.</note>
                    Copies of the notes exchanged with the British Embassy concerning the <hi
                        rend="italic">Henry L. Marshall</hi> case referred to on page seven of the
                    enclosed instruction are forwarded herewith for your information.<note n="41"
                        xml:id="d107fn41">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_163">pp. 163</ref> and <ref
                            target="#pg_165">165</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>You will observe that the extract from the <hi rend="italic">Columbia Lam
                        Review</hi> quoted in the enclosed instruction contains the following
                    statement regarding Italian laws that deal with the extent of territorial
                    jurisdiction claimed by Italy: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p rend="flushleft">“Italy requires customs manifests to be shown to her
                            officers anywhere within ten kilometers (about six miles). The Court of
                            Cassation in 1885 held that her territorial waters extend four or five
                            miles. Her neutrality laws are enforced within a zone of six and her
                            navigation laws within ten nautical miles.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>The foot-note cites the following authorities in support of this statement:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“See <hi rend="italic">Territorial Waters</hi>, an Extract from the
                            Fifteenth Annual Report of the Association for the Reform and
                            Codification of the Law of Nations (1893) 84.</p>
                        <p>“See 14 <hi rend="italic">Journal du Droit International Privé</hi>
                            (1887) 241; Crocker, <hi rend="italic">op. cit.</hi>, p. 598.</p>
                        <p>“See <hi rend="italic">Gazetta Officiate</hi> [<hi rend="italic"
                            >sic</hi>], August 16, 1914, Act No. 282, Royal Decree, No. 798<note
                                n="41a" xml:id="d107fn41a">Reference apparently incorrect; see
                                despatch no. 794, Oct. 13, 1923, from the Chargé in Italy, <ref
                                    target="#pg_195">p. 195</ref>.</note>; J. A. Hall, <hi
                                rend="italic">op. cit.</hi>, p. 130. It was formerly set at cannon
                            range. See 58 <hi rend="italic">B. &amp; F. State Papers, op. cit.</hi>,
                            p. 307; Crocker, <hi rend="italic">op. cit.</hi>, p. 530.</p>
                        <p>“See <hi rend="italic">Gazetta Officiate</hi>, 27 Juin 1912, No. 11;
                            Crocker, <hi rend="italic">op. cit.</hi>, p. 603; Naval War College
                            Topics, <hi rend="italic">op. cit</hi>. (1913) p. 24.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>[Here follows, <hi rend="italic">mutatis mutandis</hi>, the same text as in
                    instructions to the Chargé in France, September 10, 1923, beginning with “You
                    will submit,” printed on <ref target="#pg_180">pages 180</ref>–<ref
                        target="#pg_181">181</ref>.]</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles E. Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
